<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[146,771,1477,1643]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[146,242,1477,1496]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Discussion</emphasis>
. This species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[408,461,1478,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Vespidae" genus="Vespa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[408,461,1478,1496]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Vespa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a very distinctively marked black and yellow thorax, with a largely yellow metasoma. It preys on honeybees, and one species of 
<taxonomicName box="[466,582,1536,1555]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Dendrobium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[466,582,1536,1555]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Dendrobium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
orchid exploits this behavior. These orchids produce chemicals that mimic alarm pheromones of Asian (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[292,395,1595,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Apis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerana">
<emphasis box="[292,395,1595,1614]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Apis cerana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and European (
<taxonomicName box="[543,666,1594,1614]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Apis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mellifera">
<emphasis box="[543,666,1594,1614]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Apis mellifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) honeybees to attract the hornets to pollinate their flowers (
<bibRefCitation author="Brodman" box="[573,758,1624,1643]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Brodman" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1368 - 1372" refId="ref12326" refString="Brodman, J., R. Twele, F. Wittko, Y. - b. Luo, S. Xi-qiang, and M. Ayasse. 2009. Orchid mimics honey bee alarm pheromone in order to attract hornets for pollination. Current Biol. 19: 1368 - 1372." type="journal article" year="2009">Brodman et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
